n Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Horton was born in 1360, in Hardingstone, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 4 sons with Alice Eleanor Peter."},"et":{"1360–":"1360–Surnud","1364–1385":"1364–1385","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1383–Male":"1383–Surnud","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1424":"1424","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","about 1387":"umbes 1387","1360":"1360","about 1383":"umbes 1383","Hardingstone, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hardingstone, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","Coole, Cheshire, England":"Hoole, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Catton, Derbyshire, England":"Catton, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1360–":"1360–Kuollut","1364–1385":"1364–1385","